ps among Antarctic environmental managers disrupt the idea of a utopian epistemic community. O’Reilly focuses on what emerges in Antarctica among the complicated and hybrid forms of science, sociality, politics, and national membership found there. The Technocratic Antarctic unfolds the historical, political, and moral contexts that shape experiences of and decisions about the Antarctic environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental policyxAntarctica. 0aEnvironmental policyzAntarctica. 0aEthnologyxAntarctica. 0aEthnologyzAntarctica. 0aHuman ecologyxAntarctica. 0aHuman ecologyzAntarctica. 0aScientistsxAntarctica. 0aScientistszAntarctica. 4aAnthropology. 4aEnvironmental History. 4aGeneral Science.  aAntarctic, ethnographic, science, policymaking, environmental governance, Antarctic environmentalism, environmental policy, anthropology of science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170836740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501708367423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501708367/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles